in response to your overly optimistic , unk piece on how long unemployment lasts ( people patterns , sept. 20 ) :
i am in the communications field , above entry level . i was laid off in august 1988 , and after a unk and unk job search , was hired in august 1989 . my unemployment insurance ran out before i found a job ; i found cutbacks and layoffs in many companies .
the statistics quoted by the `` new '' census bureau report ( unk from 1984 to 1986 ) are out of date , certainly as an average for the northeast , and possibly for the rest of the country .
i think what bothered me most about the piece was that there seemed to be an underlying attitude to tell your readers all is well -- if you 're getting laid off do n't worry , and if you 're unk , it 's a seller 's market .
to top it off , you unk the unk showing the average number of months in a job search as `` time off . '' are you unk ? looking for a job was one of the most anxious periods of my life -- and is for most people . your paper needs a serious reality check .
