unk unk would appear to be a marketer 's dream come true . the corporate manager likes to dress unk , both on and off the job . she owns a unk in chicago and takes pride in unk it well .
yet ms. unk , in her unk , unk shopping . unk service and poor selections at many stores have turned a once favorite unk into what she calls a `` unk '' experience . these days , she would rather exercise , visit friends or read . `` if you do n't make it reasonably easy for me , '' she says of shopping , `` i 'm not going to waste my time . ''
ms. unk is far from alone . shopping has become such a unk that more people hate unk in stores than hate doing household work , according to the wall street journal 's `` american way of buying '' survey . nearly a third of the unk people interviewed by the unk peter d. hart research associates said they `` do not enjoy at all '' unk or unk . unk , unk , unk , a market research firm in unk , conn. , warns clients that americans ' love affair with shopping is on the rocks : more than half the women it has surveyed in recent years , and an even larger percentage of men , say shopping for clothes is a unk .
unk consumers -- unk jobs , families and leisure activities -- feel they have less time to shop . they also complain about unk and poorly trained salespeople , lower quality merchandise and unk prices .
but underlying these complaints is a more far-reaching change : for many shoppers , the unk is gone .
back in the 1970s , when unk were unk across the country , consumers were content to unk away an afternoon and buy whatever struck their fancy . then in the early 1980s , americans viewed shopping as a unk for the unk merchandise or the best bargains they could unk about to their friends .
now , on the unk of the 1990s , consumer researchers say that for most people , shopping is simply less fun . retailers unk unk merchandise in stores that are unk similar in appearance . shopping has become `` just one of the activities that we have to do , '' says susan unk of unk . `` it 's not an end in itself anymore . ''
in the journal poll , more than a third of the people interviewed said they probably would n't spend a free hour unk around in stores , even if a prime shopping district were nearby .
that is n't to say consumers do n't like new things . but when they go to a store today , they 're more likely to think of the trip as a mission rather than an unk . `` they 're buyers as opposed to shoppers , '' says thomas unk , a retail consultant at the accounting firm of ernst & young .
surveys and unk research show that most people are indeed shopping more unk . consumers visit fewer stores per trip ( an average of three last year , down from 3.6 in 1982 , according to consultant unk jones & co . ) and spend less time in unk ( an average of 68 minutes per trip last year , down from 90 minutes in 1982 ) . `` i leave rather than hunt for something , '' unk unk max , a unk real estate broker in new york .
despite such negative attitudes , retailers generally say consumers are n't cutting back on what they buy . `` if it is dropping off , it would be more likely that they 're shopping less often and buying more when they do shop , '' says michael unk , vice president of marketing at k mart corp .
`` there 's no question our customers ' time has become more valuable than ever , '' says stephen watson , chairman and chief executive officer of dayton hudson corp. 's department store unit . but he contends the company 's record sales and profits indicate it is making the shopping experience easier . for example , the company is hiring more sales people than in the past and paying them more . it also is laying out unk and new stores with a unk design and unk unk and elevators in more convenient central locations .
of course , there are still people for whom shopping is a unk , even a passion . but some of those people have complaints , too . take unk unk , a mother of two from norwood , mass . she often enjoys shopping , but is so fed up with the unk at a nearby unk 's department store that she unk to them as `` unk . ''
twice , mrs. unk picked merchandise off unk 's unk labeled with `` sale '' signs , only to be told when she got to the cash register that the goods were n't on special . the second time , she demanded that she receive the discount anyway , and the clerk gave in . `` i 'm willing to spend a lot of money , '' she says , `` but not if i feel like i 'm getting unk around . ''
complaints about service are so widespread that six of 10 people in the journal survey said they have unk stores because of the way they were treated . the percentage was even higher -- roughly unk -- among professionals and those earning more than $ 50,000 a year .
service has declined just at a time when consumers are more unk than ever . `` the whole tone of voice is different now in terms of what people expect from a store , '' says william unk , whose columbus , ohio , management consulting firm has surveyed consumers for more than 20 years .
despite the rising unk , few stores are making shopping more appealing . sales people unk unk still assault shoppers at many department stores , even though some consumers complain that the unk could provide a far more useful service if they were trained to operate a cash register .
consumers want selection to be easy and efficient , but that 's not what most unk want . retailers generally go to unk to keep shoppers in their stores as long as possible . many stores , for example , require customers to walk through a unk of unk designed to show off their unk just to find , say , a simple white unk . but rather than unk people to buy more , consumer researchers say , this unk just unk many shoppers . over half the respondents in the journal survey said they rarely buy on unk anyway .
so what should a retailer do ? `` those that do the best job of making the shopping experience unk and making the customer feel like a human being are very well unk , '' says leo j. shapiro , a market researcher in chicago .
he cites unk inc. , the unk department store . the chain 's strategy : pay sales people an incentive to provide good service and keep more merchandise in stock than competitors .
other retailers are trying to unk unk shoppers by doing away with their unk practice of setting high `` regular '' prices that can later be cut to `` sale '' levels . under a new approach being unk as `` everyday low pricing , '' retailers such as sears , roebuck & co. now run fewer sales . instead , they set prices between their old `` sale '' and `` regular '' prices .
last month , unk macy & co. started promising in ads that shoppers in search of women 's coats could `` cut through all the confusing sales , special buys and unk out there '' and pay what macy 's says is the `` lowest prices ... every day . ''
