with stock prices unk near record levels , a number of companies have been announcing stock unk .
but investors trying to play all the unk may find that stock unk are a lot like cotton candy : they look unk , but there 's hardly any substance . and they can even leave a unk problem , in the form of higher brokerage commissions .
`` a stock split unk by a cash dividend increase is like giving somebody five unk for a $ 5 bill . you 've got a unk unk , but it has no economic significance unk , '' says unk unk , a partner at goldman , sachs & co .
in a typical split , a company increases the number of shares it has outstanding , with each unk participating on the basis of existing holdings . with a 2-for-1 split , for example , an investor who owned 100 shares before the split would have 200 shares afterward . the stock 's price usually falls to reflect the greater number of shares , assuming no other changes at the company .
companies usually split their shares in the hope that a lower share price will attract more individual investors , increase trading volume and improve the stock 's liquidity . the theory is that a stock selling for $ 20 or $ 30 a share will be more unk to individuals than one selling for more than $ 100 -- especially for investors who like to buy round lots of 100 shares .
take l.a. gear inc. , a fast-growing designer and marketer of athletic unk that had a 2-for-1 split last month . the main reason for the split was `` to make the stock more attractive to the retail buyer , '' says elliott j. unk , the company 's executive vice president and chief financial officer .
but if a stock suddenly becomes more attractive to the unk , should n't that boost its price ? after all , l.a. gear was selling for around $ 60 a share when the split was announced on aug. 24 , then soared to more than $ 75 a share before splitting in late september . yesterday , the stock closed at $ unk .
mr. unk unk at the idea that his company 's price surge was caused by the split . `` if it were that easy to take a stock from 60 to 75 , i think a lot of other companies would be doing it , '' he says . while a split `` does create more demand for the stock , '' he says , `` i just do n't think it 's that much of a factor . ''
investment managers and others agree . while a stock split accompanied by a dividend increase can pack a powerful unk , a split by itself `` has no lasting impact on the stock price , '' says mr. unk of goldman sachs .
adds james l. unk , senior vice president at the new york stock exchange : `` we 've done research on this , and it shows a split really does n't to seem to matter significantly . ''
even if unk did affect stock prices , some unk argue that it would be unk for investors to try to take advantage of them . in their view , financial markets tend to anticipate news . thus any impact from a split would already be incorporated in a stock 's price by the time the split was announced , they argue .
`` normally , the investor is n't able to benefit '' by buying a company 's stock immediately after news of a split , says frank k. unk , a unk unk professor of finance and co-author of a 1981 study on unk . `` by the time the average investor unk the news , traders already have acted and the stock already has moved . ''
a few money managers even say a stock split sometimes may represent a sell signal . `` remember the old wall street unk : buy on the rumor and sell on the news , '' says samuel unk jr. , a managing director at unk , stevens & clark in boston .
unk can also mean a bigger expense for investors when they buy or sell shares . that 's because brokerage houses often unk their commission rates using a complex formula based partly on the number of shares being traded .
for example , a merrill lynch official says that firm 's commission on 100 shares of a $ 40 stock would be about $ 97 . but the commission would jump to about $ 115 to trade 200 shares of a $ 20 stock -- even though the dollar amount of the trade would be exactly the same . another large firm gave similar figures : the standard commission on 100 shares of a $ 40 stock would be $ 91 , but the commission would jump to $ unk to trade 200 shares of a $ 20 stock .
`` stock unk are the biggest unk on wall street , '' contends unk r. unk , a new york investor . `` the only thing that changes with a split is the brokerage commissions , and they often go up sharply . if you 're an active investor , you have to take into account the transaction costs . ''
some corporate executives also question the idea that more shares are better . among these is warren e. buffett , chairman and chief executive officer of unk unk inc. , whose stock closed yesterday on the new york stock exchange at $ unk a share .
`` we often are asked why unk does not split its stock , '' he wrote in the company 's 1983 annual report . `` the assumption behind this question usually appears to be that a split would be a unk action . we disagree . ''
in the lengthy discussion that followed , mr. buffett said : `` we want { shareholders } who think of themselves as business owners with the intention of staying a long time . and , we want those who keep their eyes focused on business results , not market prices . ''
unk his feelings on the subject , mr. buffett once sent a unk unk to a friend , unk him good health and saying : `` may you live until unk unk . ''
still , many companies like unk as an unk marketing tool that generates favorable publicity and helps broaden their shareholder base .
a stock split is `` a nice exercise in cosmetics , but that 's about all , '' says james h. unk , senior vice president and head of the unk division at cigna investments inc . `` it 's a small net positive because it can improve the unk of a particular stock . but it 's really of very little significance . ''
a split 's impact , if any , can depend on the company involved and the price of that company 's stock , says john p. rosenthal , senior partner of unk , rosenthal & co . but he adds that any impact from a split `` really is very short-term . ''
advises michael unk , a managing director at oppenheimer & co : `` just ignore unk . '' in his view , `` they 're unk for the long-term investor . look only at the fundamentals of a company , not whether it unk its stock . ''
